What could be more important
than your wedding. Whitney?

60
00:03:50.564 --> 00:03:52.556
I swear I brought your
mother up better than that.

61
00:03:52.632 --> 00:03:54.760
I really did.

62
00:03:54.901 --> 00:03:57.063
Oh. well. She's a lost cause.

63
00:03:57.137 --> 00:03:59.504
You're my only hope
for happiness now.

64
00:03:59.740 --> 00:04:04.303
Oh! Come upstairs. I've laid
out all the bridal magazines.

65
00:04:04.377 --> 00:04:07.313
Noah. take Whitney's things to the
blue room. You're in the basement.

66
00:04:07.380 --> 00:04:10.942
Oh. and see if you can find
Bruce. He'd be thrilled to see you.

67
00:04:18.225 --> 00:04:20.888
Hey. Hey. Bruce.

68
00:04:21.628 --> 00:04:22.926
- Hi.
- Hello... hello.

69
00:04:23.530 --> 00:04:24.530
Uh...

70
00:04:26.433 --> 00:04:27.433
who are you?

71
00:04:28.168 --> 00:04:29.568
Uh. Noah.

72
00:04:31.605 --> 00:04:33.267
Noah. Noah Solloway?

73
00:04:33.340 --> 00:04:35.605
- I'm your ex...
- Oh. oh. Yes. of course.

74
00:04:35.675 --> 00:04:37.735
I'm so sorry. Uh. Bruce Butler.

75
00:04:38.512 --> 00:04:40.174
Margaret told me
you were coming.

76
00:04:40.647 --> 00:04:41.647
The writer.

77
00:04:42.082 --> 00:04:44.313
She says you've
published multiple books.

78
00:04:44.384 --> 00:04:47.286
- That's right. yeah.
- Wow. that's impressive.

79
00:04:48.955 --> 00:04:50.947
You know. there's
a great expression.

80
00:04:51.124 --> 00:04:52.124
Uh...

81
00:04:53.393 --> 00:04:56.386
"No one has one
book in him. but..."

82
00:04:56.630 --> 00:04:58.360
Um. It's. uh...

83
00:04:58.431 --> 00:05:00.730
I think it's. "Everyone
has one book in them.

84
00:05:00.801 --> 00:05:02.497
Almost nobody has two."

85
00:05:04.204 --> 00:05:05.467
Oh. Oh.

86
00:05:06.373 --> 00:05:07.671
That's not very nice.

87
00:05:08.141 --> 00:05:11.270
Uh. you know. I always
wanted to be a writer.

88
00:05:11.444 --> 00:05:14.471
but there never seemed to
be enough hours in the day.

89
00:05:14.714 --> 00:05:15.714
Yeah.

90
00:05:15.749 --> 00:05:16.842
Are you hungry?

91
00:05:17.083 --> 00:05:20.247
I was craving some.
uh. some of these. uh...

92
00:05:20.887 --> 00:05:21.786
- some of these...
- Here.

93
00:05:21.855 --> 00:05:25.519
- Bruce. let me make those for you.
- No. No. no. you're our guest. you know.

94
00:05:25.592 --> 00:05:27.959
Have some coffee.

95
00:05:28.395 --> 00:05:32.628
Uh. I have no idea
how to use that machine.

96
00:05:32.699 --> 00:05:34.099
Sure. I'll make some.

97
00:05:35.402 --> 00:05:39.271
Um. are you. uh. you married?

98
00:05:40.640 --> 00:05:43.303
Uh. no. Divorced.

99
00:05:44.044 --> 00:05:45.239
Twice. actually.

100
00:05:45.312 --> 00:05:48.510
Well. that's probably why
you have so much time to write.

101
00:05:48.782 --> 00:05:50.910
I'm more of a
family man. myself.

102
00:05:52.686 --> 00:05:53.881
Bruce. no!

103
00:05:54.020 --> 00:05:55.955
- Bruce!
- Oh. Jesus.

104
00:05:58.091 --> 00:05:59.354
It's okay.

105
00:05:59.426 --> 00:06:01.122
- No...
- I just. I just wanted to...

106
00:06:01.194 --> 00:06:03.459
It's all right. it's all right.

107
00:06:05.365 --> 00:06:09.632
We're trying to set boundaries
for Bruce. some new expectations.

108
00:06:09.703 --> 00:06:12.114
While you're here. I'd appreciate
it if you could help with that.

109
00:06:12.138 --> 00:06:13.618
I'm sorry. I didn't...
I didn't know.

110
00:06:13.807 --> 00:06:14.866
Well. now you do.

111
00:06:17.477 --> 00:06:18.477
Hi.

112
00:06:18.879 --> 00:06:20.848
What are you doing here?

113
00:06:20.914 --> 00:06:24.612
- I'm getting married.
- What? To this fellow?

114
00:06:24.784 --> 00:06:27.117
Why. Helly-Belly.
that's fantastic.

115
00:06:27.320 --> 00:06:28.998
Does this mean that
you've finally broken up

116
00:06:29.022 --> 00:06:32.459
with that kid from Pennsylvania.
the one that was practically a mute?

117
00:06:32.525 --> 00:06:34.357
Bruce. this is Whitney. She's...

118
00:06:34.427 --> 00:06:37.363
Helen is your daughter.
This is your granddaughter.

119
00:06:38.031 --> 00:06:39.465
G-Granddaughter?

120
00:06:39.633 --> 00:06:40.794
I can't do this anymore.

121
00:06:40.867 --> 00:06:43.462
It's okay. Margaret. it's okay.
Let's focus on the wedding. Uh...

122
00:06:43.570 --> 00:06:47.371
Whitney has this huge agenda for
us. and. uh. she needs your help.

123
00:06:47.440 --> 00:06:48.840
Uh. that's right. Grandma.

124
00:06:48.909 --> 00:06:51.936
Um. I need to
decide on a florist.

125
00:06:52.012 --> 00:06:54.690
I've narrowed it down to three.
but I'm sure you'll have an opinion.

126
00:06:54.714 --> 00:06:57.013
Um. I need to
figure out a caterer.

127
00:06:57.317 --> 00:06:59.195
I wanted to find somebody
who could do vegan options.

128
00:06:59.219 --> 00:07:00.585
I don't know if
you know anybody.

129
00:07:00.754 --> 00:07:03.451
And. um... Oh. well.
we already got a tent.

130
00:07:03.523 --> 00:07:05.992
Oh. that reminds me.
The bill for the tent came.

131
00:07:08.662 --> 00:07:11.632
Margaret. I'm... I thought
I was doing the catering.

132
00:07:11.698 --> 00:07:13.242
and you and Bruce were
gonna pay for the tent.

133
00:07:13.266 --> 00:07:16.668
Noah. we can't pay
for this. It's $20.000.

134
00:07:18.204 --> 00:07:19.069
We don't have any money.

135
00:07:19.139 --> 00:07:21.699
And whose fault is
that. Marie Antoinette?

136
00:07:23.910 --> 00:07:27.347
Whitney. I just
had a splendid idea.

137
00:07:27.781 --> 00:07:30.341
Why don't I call Dean
at our tennis club?

138
00:07:30.417 --> 00:07:32.443
They do a marvelous brunch.

139
00:07:32.519 --> 00:07:35.648
And if we do the wedding
reception outside of peak hours.

140
00:07:35.722 --> 00:07:39.022
I'm sure we can get a
discount on the cabana.

141
00:07:39.259 --> 00:07:43.128
They have a waffle station and
a make-your-own-omelet bar.

142
00:07:43.930 --> 00:07:44.989
Excuse me. please.

143
00:07:49.402 --> 00:07:52.236
Okay. Margaret. the
wedding is happening here.

144
00:07:52.906 --> 00:07:54.169
Okay? So. if you want to help.

145
00:07:54.741 --> 00:07:56.972
help us figure out a
way to make that happen.

146
00:08:01.781 --> 00:08:02.781
Hey.

147
00:08:06.786 --> 00:08:08.516
We can't afford a
wedding. can we?

148
00:08:09.089 --> 00:08:11.320
No one can afford a
wedding. not really.

149
00:08:11.458 --> 00:08:12.517
We can figure it out.

150
00:08:12.726 --> 00:08:14.820
No. I need to get
back to reality.

151
00:08:14.894 --> 00:08:17.659
I... Work has been crazy. I had
to miss three days to be here.

152
00:08:17.731 --> 00:08:19.893
Andrea already
wants to fucking kill me.

153
00:08:20.533 --> 00:08:21.728
It's fine. We'll just...

154
00:08:22.602 --> 00:08:24.070
we'll get married at city hall.

155
00:08:24.170 --> 00:08:26.530
Come on. Whitney. you've been
talking about having a wedding

156
00:08:26.573 --> 00:08:28.667
in this house since
before you were in braces.

157
00:08:28.742 --> 00:08:30.586
I already found a red-eye
that we can get on tonight.

158
00:08:30.610 --> 00:08:32.010
It has seats available.

159
00:08:32.178 --> 00:08:35.012
Give me six hours.
okay? Let's at least try.

160
00:08:35.548 --> 00:08:38.382
Then if you still want to go to
city hall. then we'll go to city hall.

161
00:08:38.785 --> 00:08:39.905
Come on. Have you got a pen?

162
00:08:47.327 --> 00:08:48.556
Right. what's the first thing?

163
00:08:48.928 --> 00:08:50.260
- Um...
- Tent.

164
00:08:51.331 --> 00:08:53.242
Okay. I just received the
last part of my advance.

165
00:08:53.266 --> 00:08:55.144
and I can't think of a
better thing to spend it on.

166
00:08:55.168 --> 00:08:57.228
- Dad. no.
- So that's that done.

167
00:08:57.303 --> 00:08:58.543
- Next?
- Dad. you don't get it.

168
00:08:58.772 --> 00:09:01.708
A tent is no good if you
don't have things to put in it.

169
00:09:01.808 --> 00:09:03.276
Backyard weddings
are so expensive

170
00:09:03.343 --> 00:09:06.643
because you have to pay for
every single little thing. See?

171
00:09:09.682 --> 00:09:11.412
Okay.

172
00:09:11.785 --> 00:09:13.219
Let's start with plates.

173
00:09:15.622 --> 00:09:17.542
Well. this house has got
to have plenty of those.

174
00:09:18.825 --> 00:09:22.489
I always hoped your
mother would inherit this.

175
00:09:22.562 --> 00:09:24.121
but she insists
on feeding you all

176
00:09:24.297 --> 00:09:27.290
from earthenware as if
she grew up on a riverbank.

177
00:09:27.367 --> 00:09:30.269
But no matter. because now it'll
go to someone who appreciates it.

178
00:09:30.336 --> 00:09:33.101
- Thank you. Grandma.
- This is helpful.

179
00:09:33.840 --> 00:09:34.967
Thanks. What's next?

180
00:09:35.241 --> 00:09:36.140
Oh. I have an appointment

181
00:09:36.209 --> 00:09:39.805
at an East Hampton bridal boutique
at 2:00. but it's crazy expensive.

182
00:09:39.879 --> 00:09:42.508
- I think we should cancel it.
- You don't have a dress yet?

183
00:09:42.582 --> 00:09:44.244
Perfect. Come on. let's go.

184
00:09:44.984 --> 00:09:46.577
Oh. Margaret. can
we borrow your car?

185
00:09:46.653 --> 00:09:48.952
- Only if Whitney drives.
- Why?

186
00:09:49.055 --> 00:09:52.787
Because the last time you drove a car
in Montauk. you killed Scott Lockhart.

187
00:10:02.235 --> 00:10:04.295
So. what do you want
to do about music?

188
00:10:04.671 --> 00:10:05.969
You want dancing. right?

189
00:10:06.573 --> 00:10:08.667
Honestly. I kind of
wanted a flash mob.

190
00:10:09.375 --> 00:10:11.401
- What?
- You know. a flash mob?

191
00:10:11.478 --> 00:10:13.845
It's. like. a surprise dance.
but everyone knows the steps.

192
00:10:14.614 --> 00:10:17.049
How could everybody know
the steps to a surprise dance?

193
00:10:17.117 --> 00:10:19.597
Because somebody teaches
them ahead of time. and it's like a...

194
00:10:20.453 --> 00:10:21.453
Never mind.

195
00:10:24.424 --> 00:10:25.824
Oh. look.

196
00:10:28.561 --> 00:10:31.001
We have to stop and see what
they've done to the Lobster Roll.

197
00:10:31.097 --> 00:10:35.159
- No. Whitney. we don't have time.
- Yes. we do. Come on. It'll be hilarious.

198
00:10:58.925 --> 00:11:00.359
Hi. we okay here?

199
00:11:04.364 --> 00:11:06.356
- Not as friendly as they used to be.
- Yeah.

200
00:11:12.472 --> 00:11:15.374
Hey. remember when Stacey
almost choked and mom saved her?

201
00:11:16.442 --> 00:11:17.442
What?

202
00:11:17.677 --> 00:11:19.288
Yeah. you remember.
We were sitting right there.

203
00:11:19.312 --> 00:11:20.856
and Trevor and Stacey
were playing that game.

204
00:11:20.880 --> 00:11:22.974
and then Stacey put
a marble in her mouth.

205
00:11:24.117 --> 00:11:26.313
No. it wasn't. uh. it wasn't
your mom who saved her.

206
00:11:26.386 --> 00:11:27.911
It was Alison.

207
00:11:29.455 --> 00:11:30.455
What?

208
00:11:30.757 --> 00:11:33.757
- No. that's not how I remember it at all.
- No. I'm pretty sure it was her.

209
00:11:33.826 --> 00:11:36.261
Stacey was choking
and Alison was right there.

210
00:11:42.101 --> 00:11:44.127
So. was that the
day you met Alison?

211
00:11:45.972 --> 00:11:47.167
Yeah. I think it was.

212
00:11:49.242 --> 00:11:51.768
So. you bonded over the fact that
Stacey almost choked to death?

213
00:11:53.846 --> 00:11:55.724
Whitney. if you ever want
to talk about what happened

214
00:11:55.748 --> 00:11:57.308
- between Alison and me...
- Yeah. sure.

215
00:11:57.383 --> 00:11:58.646
I do. actually. Go ahead.

216
00:12:01.221 --> 00:12:03.465
Well. it's not... I didn't exactly
have a prepared speech. but...

217
00:12:03.489 --> 00:12:04.684
Yeah. that's what I thought.

218
00:12:04.757 --> 00:12:06.817
No. I mean. if you want
to ask questions about it...

219
00:12:06.893 --> 00:12:08.384
- Stop.
- Noah?

220
00:12:09.963 --> 00:12:10.987
Luisa. hi.

221
00:12:11.331 --> 00:12:13.732
- Hey.
- Hey. you remember Whitney. my daughter?

222
00:12:13.800 --> 00:12:16.634
Yeah. of course. Uh. I babysat
you one summer at the Butlers'.

223
00:12:16.703 --> 00:12:18.137
I remember. Nice to see you.

224
00:12:18.371 --> 00:12:21.432
Yeah. we're in town planning
Whitney's wedding. if you can believe it.

225
00:12:22.075 --> 00:12:24.408
Cool. Congratulations.

226
00:12:24.744 --> 00:12:25.744
Thank you.

227
00:12:26.379 --> 00:12:27.677
So. this is different.

228
00:12:28.982 --> 00:12:32.544
Yeah. It's officially in the
hands of the new owners now.

229
00:12:32.719 --> 00:12:35.348
I just came by to empty a
few things out of the office.

230
00:12:35.755 --> 00:12:37.849
Ah. End of an era.

231
00:12:39.092 --> 00:12:40.092
Yep.

232
00:12:42.195 --> 00:12:43.288
I have to get going.

233
00:12:43.529 --> 00:12:45.225
What's. uh. what's next for you?

234
00:12:46.432 --> 00:12:48.298
I'm going back to New York.

235
00:12:48.835 --> 00:12:50.736
- Really? Wow.
- Mm-hmm.

236
00:12:50.870 --> 00:12:53.362
I can't believe you got
Cole to go to the city.

